HEADWORD: Steed
<hw>Steed</hw> <pr>(st⟦emac⟧d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>stede</ets>, AS. <ets>st⟦emac⟧da</ets> a stud-horse, war horse, fr.
<ets>st⟦omac⟧d</ets> a stud of breeding steeds; akin to G.
<ets>stute</ets> a mare, Icel. <ets>stedda</ets>,
<ets>st⟦omac⟧⟦edh⟧</ets>, a stud. ⟦root⟧163. See <er>Stud</er> of
horses.]</ety> <def>A horse, especially a spirited horse for state or
war; -- used chiefly in poetry or stately prose.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A knight
upon a <xex>steed</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mounted upon a hot and fiery <qex>steed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Steedless</ent>⟦br⟧
